The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, December 25, 2003  The City Diary
																																																																																		Calcutta High Court on Thursday refused to pass a stay order on a government notification asking vehicle-owners to pay a one-time five-year road tax from November 1, 2003. The court, however, extended the last date for paying the road tax for the owners of two-wheelers till January 7, 2004. The government notification had asked two-wheeler owners to pay a road tax by December 31, 2003. The court will hear both cases after the Christmas vacation of the high court.																																																		The division bench of Justice A.K. Ganguly and Justice D.P. Sengupta on Thursday delivered a judgment upholding the amendment in the Central Valuation Act in which the state government had empowered municipalities to assess taxes on properties owned by common people. A welfare organisation had challenged the constitutional validity of the move. Henceforth, the municipalities will also enjoy the right of determining tax on the properties on the basis of the valuation. 																																																		Students of Howrah Bijoykrishna Girls College on Wednesday gheraoed their principal Tapati Mukherjee for seven hours protesting the authorities decision not to allow them to appear in the 2004 Part II exams of Calcutta University for not having the required attendance.																																																		Justice Barin Ghosh of Calcutta High Court on Thursday observed that the government hospital authorities should allow a patient suffering from a heart block the right to choose the type of pacemaker before it is implanted in her/him by a surgeon. The observation was made while hearing a petition filed by a company alleging that the state hospital authorities were using low grade foreign pacemakers neglecting the ones made in India and offered at relatively cheaper rates. 																																																		Romanian President Ion Iliescu will dedicate Park Street to the memory of Mother Teresa during his three-day visit to India ending on December 31. Mayor Subrata Mukherjee said the city civic authorities had decided to rename Park Street as Mother Teresa Sarani. The mayor has decided to rename a part of Ripon Street after scholar Mircea Eliade at the request of the Romanian consulate. Eliade came to Calcutta in 1928 and studied Sanskrit and Indian philosophy under Professor Surendranath Dasgupta, father of Maitreyee Devi.																																																		Fire broke out on Wednesday afternoon in a civil defence godown on Jheel Road, in the Cossipore police station area. According to police, it took six fire tenders and an hour to douse the flames.																																																		Apollo Medical Research Institute Hospital in collaboration with Asian Institute of Dermatology will start its dermatology and cosmetic surgery centre at the AMRI clinic from February 2004. TO Chittaranjan Cancer Research  Institute for launching a programme to check blood samples  of CMC sweepers at Dhapa for HIV and Hepatitis-B
